\begin_layout Standard
(Basically, don't add parameters that don't improve your fit).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Measure your test-statistic 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D=2\Sigma(f_{complex}-y_{obs})^{2}-2\Sigma(f_{simpler}-y_{obs})^{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{complex}$
\end_inset

 are the calculated values for the complex model, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{simpler}$
\end_inset

 are the calculated values for the simpler model, and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{obs}$
\end_inset

 is the real set of observations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the difference in the complexity of the complex and simple models
 by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n_{df}=n_{complex}-n_{simpler}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{df}$
\end_inset

 is the difference in the number of degrees of freedom, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{complex}$
\end_inset

 is the number of fitting parameters for the complex model, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{simpler}$
\end_inset

 is the number of fitting parameters for the simpler model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Look up a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 value from a 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 distribution using 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 as your test statistic and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{df}$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 This will give you a 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 value for accepting or rejecting the new model.
 
\end_layout

